sql:
SELECT case_type_name, description
FROM case_types
WHERE severity_level >= 4;

external_knowledge:
- 'Top 3 cases by count' refers to the three most frequent case types reported each year;
- 'Summary reports' are detailed documents that provide an overview of the cases and their outcomes;
- The year is extracted from the report generation date to match with the case year.

- Severity levels are rated from 1 to 5, with 5 being the most severe;
- 'Severe crimes' refer to cases with a severity level greater than 3;
- 'Instances of severe crimes' refers to the number of cases reported in the year 2023.

- 'Sexual Assault on a Minor' and 'Assault with Child' are specific types of cases that are being tracked;
- User activity is measured by the number of access events, views, and edits;
- The query is intended to provide a comprehensive overview of case statistics and user activity across different counties.

- "Unique cases" refers to distinct case IDs;
- "Woven through the system" refers to cases that have been processed and recorded in the database;
- " Layers of detail" refers to the hierarchical structure of cases and their detailed entries;
- "Guardians of the law" refers to users who access the case data;
- "Revisited by the guardians of the law" refers to the access logs of the cases.
